" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 271 "3. \+
 Fundamental Theorem of Algebra.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra a
sserts that every non-constant polynomial (with complex-valued coeffic
ients) has a root (a zero, a solution).  A consequence of the Fundamen
tal Theorem of Algebra is that every polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 
276 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 13 " has exactly " }{TEXT 277 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 108 
" roots.  An alternate formulation of this consequence would be that e
very non-constant polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 279 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 
38 " can be factored into a product of a  " }{TEXT 278 1 "n" }{TEXT 
-1 16 " linear factors." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 
