1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A related theorem about find
ing roots of polynomials (equivalently factoring polynomials into a pr
oduct of linear factors) asserts that if the polynomial has real coeff
icients -- all of the polynomials we have considered (and will conside
r) have had real coefficients -- then any complex roots (or factors) m
ust occur in conjugate pairs.  For example, both the complex factors o
f " }{TEXT 288 5 "F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 289 2 "H " }{TEXT 
-1 236 "(above) all occurred in conjugate pairs.  Demonstrate this the
orem by creating three new polynomials, name them F1, G1 and H1, of de
gree 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show that the any complex factors of F1, G
1 and H1 occur in conjugate pairs." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
